[2] USA (Wisconsin)
Date: 20 Feb 2014
Source: WHBL [edited]
http://whbl.com/news/articles/2014/feb/21/health-officials-stress-vaccinations-after-measles-cases-are-spotted-in-wisconsin/


Health officials are reminding people to get vaccinated after 2 cases of measles were spotted in Wisconsin. The 2 people apparently contracted the highly contagious disease while travelling overseas.

Marathon County public health nurse Becky Mroczenski says that's the most common way people catch the measles these days. "Because of so much travel now, a person can come into the state with measles and spread it to people who are susceptible."

The 2 cases are in southern Wisconsin and were apparently unrelated. Mroczenski says vaccinations among the population kept it from being worse than it could have been. "This time it's not an outbreak, but certainly it can become one very quickly, because measles will spread quite easily and rapidly."

She says that's why it's so important to be vaccinated. "When what we call herd immunity levels aren't high enough, we can have breakthrough cases which can worsen the spread or cause an outbreak."

Measles is spread through the air and is highly contagious. A person with measles can spread the disease even before they know they have it because the symptoms are like the cold or the flu. "Because we don't see much of it, it's typically misdiagnosed at first. Practitioners aren't used to seeing it, because the vaccine has done such a wonderful job of keeping it at bay."

If you don't have the vaccine or don't know if you have it, contact your local health department or your health practitioner for more information.

[Byline: Raymond Neupert]

