[6] Canada (Alberta)
Date: 22 Feb 2014
Source: Edmonton Journal [edited]
http://www.edmontonjournal.com/case+measles+confirmed+central+Alberta/9537201/story.html


A case of measles has been confirmed in central Alberta in addition to 2 probable cases, Alberta Health Services says.

AHS is advising Red Deer area residents to take precautions to protect themselves against the highly infectious disease. "There's a possibility of it spreading further, said AHS Central Zone medical officer Dr. Ifeoma Achebe. "Chances are that people might catch it, and measles is an extremely contagious disease," Achebe said.

Achebe said they are hoping to keep possible infection numbers low by raising awareness about what the public should do if symptoms of measles present themselves. "They should not go to the hospital or the clinic. They stand the risk of putting other people at the risk of catching the disease, so we recommend that they call Health Link," she said.

There is no treatment for measles, which is why Achebe stressed the importance of immunization. "Immunization remains the one way that we can prevent the spread of measles," she said. The measles vaccine is typically given to children when they are a year old. The booster shot is then given between ages 4 and 6. The measles vaccine is free of charge in Alberta.

The outbreak in central Alberta is not linked to the Nov 2013 outbreak in the Lethbridge region, Achebe said. That outbreak was officially declared over by the AHS in early January 2014. There were 42 confirmed cases.

Measles symptoms include fever, cough, runny nose, red eyes, and a blotchy rash that starts on the head and face and spreads down the body.

To contact Alberta Health Link visit http://myhealth.alberta.ca or call 1-866-408-5465.

[Byline: Kathleen Charlebois]

